    title: "Basic Syntax, Variables, Data Types & Operators",
    questionLimit: 20,
    timeLimit: 5,
    summary: "Python is highly case-sensitive and uses whitespace (indentation) as a core syntax element — improper indentation causes errors. Python variable names can be up to 255 characters, must start with a letter or underscore, and may contain alphanumeric characters and underscores. Python supports integer, float, string, boolean, and complex data types without requiring explicit declarations, since types are inferred dynamically. Variables store values assigned with the = operator. Python supports arithmetic operators (+, -, *, /, %, **, //), relational operators (<, >, ==, <=, >=, !=) — all producing boolean results — and logical operators (and, or, not). Type conversion functions int(), float(), str() and the type() function are built in. The # character comments a single line. Python supports two modes: Interactive Mode (>>> prompt for immediate scripting) and Code/Normal Mode (for writing complete programs). Output is displayed using print and input is read with raw_input(). PHP is also case-sensitive for variables but whitespace-insensitive. All PHP variables begin with a dollar sign ($). PHP variable names start with a letter or underscore and may contain a-z, A-Z, 0-9, and _. PHP commands end with a semicolon. PHP supports eight data types: Integers, Doubles, Booleans, NULL, Strings, Arrays, Objects, and Resources. PHP arithmetic operators include + - * / % ++ --. PHP logical operators include && (and), || (or), ! (not), xor. Relational operators cover == != > < >= <=. Assignment operators include = += -= *= /= .= %=. PHP comments use // for single lines and /* */ for multi-line blocks. PHP output is produced with echo (no return value, faster, can take multiple parameters) and print (return value of 1, takes only one argument).",
