    summary: "A subprogram is a named block of code that performs a specific task, possibly acting on parameters and possibly returning a value. Subprograms have a single entry point and, when called, suspend the calling program during execution before returning control to the caller. Benefits include reduced compile time (compiled only once per page in PHP), improved reliability (bugs fixed in one place), and improved readability. Key terminology: subprogram definition (interface + actions), header (name, kind, formal parameters), parameter profile/signature (number, order, types of parameters), formal parameters (dummy variables in the definition), and actual parameters (values or addresses in the call statement). Python functions are created with 'def'; the first string in the body (Docstring) is accessible via function_name.__doc__. Python supports normal parameters, default parameters (optional, with assigned defaults), parameter lists (*args — variable number via tuple reference), and keyword parameters (**kwargs). Python arguments are passed by assignment (call-by-reference — changing a parameter changes the original). The return statement returns zero or more values; multiple values return as a tuple. Python also supports lambda: anonymous, one-line, expression-only functions (e.g., determinant = lambda a, b, c: b**2 + 4*a*c). In PHP, functions are defined with 'function'; names are case-insensitive. PHP parameter types: default parameters (must follow non-default parameters), variable parameters (using func_num_args(), func_get_arg(), func_get_args()), and missing parameters (generate warnings). PHP supports two parameter-passing modes: by value (copy of value, original unaffected) and by reference (using & before parameter, function gets direct access to original variable). PHP functions return a single value with 'return'; multiple values require returning an array; if no return is provided, NULL is returned. PHP anonymous functions (closures) can be assigned to variables or passed directly to other functions.",
